class Solution {
    public String findDifferentBinaryString(String[] nums) {
        StringBuilder sb=new StringBuilder();
        for(int i=0;i<nums.length;i++){
            char ch=nums[i].charAt(i);
            if(ch=='0') sb.append('1');
            else sb.append('0');
        }
        return sb.toString();
    }
}

Steps: Take the i-th string and look at the i-th character in that string. Flip the bit (if it is 0 change it to 1, and 
if it is 1 change it to 0). Add this flipped bit to the result string. Repeat this process for all n strings.
Example: Input = ["01","10"]. For i = 0, the string is "01". The 0th bit is 0, so flip it to 1 → result becomes "1". For i = 1, 
the string is "10". The 1st bit is 0, so flip it to 1 → result becomes "11". Output: "11".
